@NODE Game_Menu "Game Menu"

   The In-Game Menu Options are as follows:

   Before a game, each player must design their army.  Armies may be created
from any combination of troops (Soldiers, Tanks, or Planes).  Each troop
type has it's own pre-designed standard sub-types, which can be added by
clicking on the relevant button.
   To design custom Tanks or Planes, click on the Design button from the
relevant menu to enter the design screen.  Clicking with the left mouse
button on one of the characteristic buttons will add one point to that
characteristic, the right button will remove one point.
   To remove a troop, click on the Remove button, then on the relevant
troop.
   When done creating your army, click Done to let the next player create
their army.  When all the armies are ready, the landscape will be generated
and the game will begin.

   During the game:

   During the game, the computer will operate its tanks and civilians etc.
When a human player's troops need moving, the display will center on the
troop to be moved next.

   Clicking with the right mouse button at the edges of the map area will
scroll the map view.  Clicking with the left mouse button will cause the
tank to try to move towards the selected point.

   Selecting the Map button will bring up the full area map.  Clicking on
this map will zoom in on the selected area.  Clicking anywhere outside it
will return to the old zoomed area view.

   For normal troops, there will also be four firing buttons displayed -
Aimed, Standard, Autoshot and Snapshot.  Aimed shots double accuracy and
cost 8 points.  Standard shots give normal accuracy and cost 4 points.
Autoshots give three shots at 1/4 accuracy, costing 5 points.  Snapshots
give 1/2 accuracy and cost 2 points.  If the troop selected does not have
the required number of points then clicking a firing button will do nothing.

   Indirect firing troops only have one firing button, Indirect.  Indirect
fire costs 15 points, at extremely low accuracy, but these shots are do not
require line of site to the target.

   Clicking on the CONCEDE button will remove that player from the game -
their troops will, however, remain on the battlefield until the end of the
battle and may still be destroyed, as may normal troops.  They may not,
however, be moved or made to fire.  Troops belonging to a side that has
conceded are not displayed on the map view.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Registration "Registering Warhost"

   Warhost is a shareware game.  That is, it may be copied freely in accordance
with @{"Copyright Notice" LINK Copyright} given.  Most of the new features
introduced in this version are only available if a valid registration key is
present in the correct location on your system.  To obtain this key, you
must send a cheque for five pounds Sterling to the author's address, along
with your name.  You will then be sent either a disk containing your
individual registration key, or a UUencoded email containing the key,
whichever you prefer.  Keys sent by email will take less time to be
processed.  Keys sent on disk through the post will unfortunately have to be
sent on standard 720K format PC disks, since I may not always have access to
an Amiga to make keys on.  These disks may be read by CrossDOS, which is
bundled with OS2.x+ and is fairly easy to use.  Under OS3.x, it can be
loaded by double clicking on the PC0 icon in the DOSDrivers directory of the
Storage disk.

   See the @{" Contacting S.C.R " LINK Contact} screen for the address to
write to in order to register.

   If you choose not to register then that's fine, it's perfectly legal not
to, because the unregistered version is shareware.  It is illegal, however,
to copy the registration key for use by anyone else, or to modify the
executable in such a way as to bypass the key authorisation!

@ENDNODE

