@NODE Opt_Game "Game Options Menu"

   The Game Options menu lets the user edit the following properties:

   ARMIES:
      Sets the number of players in the game.  There can be from 1 to 4
      players, although 1 player mode is played as a battle against the
      computer and is not very difficult or fun. =<

   ROUNDS:
      Sets the number of rounds in the match, from 1 to 5.  Before each
      round, players are given some extra points with which to build new
      tanks.  Points may be carried over from previous rounds.  Any tanks
      remaining at the end of a round may be carried over into the next.

   SOLDIERS: (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not soldiers feature in the game.  Currently, this
      only causes the driver of any tank to appear in its place when it
      is destroyed.

   PLANES:   (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not planes are available when designing armies to
      play.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Opt_Comp "Computer Player Options"

   This screen allows the user to decide which computer-run players to
   include in the game.

   TANKS:
      Sets whether or not the computer will generate "neutral" tanks which
      will attack anyone and everyone.....

   PEOPLE:
      Sets whether or not the computer will generate extra civilians who
      will then wander around getting run over and shot.....

   ANIMALS: (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not the computer will produce herds of sheep and cows
      which wander around randomly and tend to set off mines.....

@ENDNODE

@NODE OptGfx "Graphics Options Menu"

   This menu allows some of the graphical display aspects of the game to
   be configured.

   MAP ALL/MAP OWN:
      Sets whether each player gets to see all the active tanks or only
      their own when viewing the full map.

   MOVES: SEE ALL/SEE OWN  (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not all movement is displayed on screen, or whether
      animal, civilian and enemy tank movement is not displayed.

   EXPLODE DELAY: (REGISTERED)
      Sets the delay in frames between successive explosions in a chain
      reaction being displayed.  A value of 0 will cause all explosions
      to be displayed simultaneously as one large explosion, while a value
      of 8 will cause each level of chain reaction explosions to be
      displayed entirely seperately.

   FIRES ON/OFF:  (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not explosions can cause fires.  If set to on then any
      feature destroyed by an explosion stands a chance of catching on fire.

   SMOKE ON/OFF:  (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not fires produce smoke.  Smoke has no effect on the
      mechanics of the game, but can add atmosphere to a battle.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Opt_Set "Miscellaneous Settings Menu"

   This menu is split inot two pages, containing miscellanous options for
   the game.

PAGE 1:

   DAMAGE 1+/0+: (REGISTERED)
      Sets the minimum damage caused by a single shot.  This may be 1,
      indicating that every hit causes at least one point of damage, or 0,
      indicating that successful hits may cause no damage if the attacker's
      strength is sufficiently low.  The default is 1+.

   FX ON/OFF:  (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not damage effects tanks abilities.  Currently, this
      setting has no effect on the game, but may do in future versions.

   ROUTING (AUTO/MANUAL):  (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not the computer attempts to find the best path round
      obstacles and across hazardous terrain, or whether the user must
      choose a path manually.  The default is automatic.

   NEXT:
      Switches to the second page of misc. settings.


PAGE 2:

   FIRE ARC (LIMITED/ANY): (REGISTERED)
      Determines whether or not the fire arc of aeroplanes is limited.
      If limited arc of fire is set the a plane may only fire at targets
      within 45 degrees of the direction in which it is pointing.  This
      option does not affect tanks, which are assumed to have 360 degree
      fire with their turrets.  The default is Any.

   SNAPFIRE ON/OFF: (REGISTERED)
      Sets whether or not tanks with movement points remaining at the end
      of their turn will go into an "overwatch" state.  If snapfire is on
      then tanks with movement points remaining will fire upon any enemy
      tank moving or firing within about ten squares of them, if a line
      of sight can be traced.  This may result in a tank catching itself in
      the burst effect of its own snapfire.  A snapfire shot is equivalent
      to a snap shot.  The default is snapfire off.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Opt_Map "Map Design Options Menu"

   This menu consists of a number of pages of options controlling the
   features generated on the game landscape.

PAGE 1:

   BARRELS:
      The barrels buttons allow barrels to be switched on or off, as in
      version 0.0.  In addition, registered users can set the number of
      barrels to be placed on the map.

   MINES:
      Mines may be turned on or off.  Registered users may also set the
      number of mines placed on the map, on a scale of 1 to 100.

PAGE 2:

   SAND:    (REGISTERED)
      Sand may be turned on or off, and the percentage coverage of the map
with sand may also be set.

   ROCKS:   (REGISTERED)
      Rocks may be turned on or off and the percentage map coverage of rocks
set.  Setting both sand and rocks to 100% will result in a rocky landscape,
since rocks take priority over sand.

PAGE 3:

   RIVERS:  (REGISTERED)
      Rivers may be turned on or off and the number of rivers generated may
      be set on a scale of 1 to 5.

   ROADS:   (REGISTERED)
      Two roads may be generated, which cross the map diagonally.  These
      roads may be tarmac or dirt tracks, or may be turned off entirely.

PAGE 4:

   TREES:   (REGISTERED)
      Trees may be turned on or off.  The percentage map coverage with trees
      may also be set.  High percentages tend to increase the time to
      generate a map exponentially.

   FIELDS:  (REGISTERED)
      Fields may be turned on or off, as well as the percentage map coverage
      of fields being set.  Fields will cover roads, but will be covered
      over by buildings.  Trees will also grow on fields.

PAGE 5:

   BUILDINGS:     (REGISTERED)
      Buildings may be turned on or off and the percentage coverage of
      buildings on the map set, allowing maps to vary from cities (75%+) to
      rural landscapes with scatterings of houses (10%-).

   BASES ON/OFF:  (REGISTERED)
      The bases that appear in the corners of the map may be turned on or
      off.  Bases serve no real purpose, except that they go boom
      satisfyingly if shot at enough.

PAGE 6:

   LAKES:
      Lakes may be turned on or off.  The number of lakes generated may be
      set, as may the size of the lakes.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "Installation:"

   To install Warhost, copy the game file to the directory of your choice.
   Copy the contents of the Fonts subdirectory from this distribution into
your own system fonts: drawer.  You may need to run fixfonts to get the
system to register the new font.
   Warhost will run from any directory perfectly happily but will need to
store registration and game options files in the S: directory if the game
is registered.  You should therefore ensure that the S: directory is
available and not write-protected when saving the game options.

   Warhost has been tested on:

   A1200/030 @50MHz with 4Mb Fast RAM and 512Mb HD
   Standard A1200, no HD, no Fast RAM, no nothing.
   DosUAE020 Emulator with Sound enabled, 256 colours non-dithered,
      2Mb chip, no Fast RAM, under Win95, using a directory as hard
      the Amiga hard drive and with a Kickstart 3.0 ROM-file.

   (Note that anything lower than an A1200 will really crawl)

@ENDNODE

